YAtPAL2rDH7KVlHg3KQlEmijSaEjGL_5TER51dPP0vCdDH39PjeVd3hYNyK8Dm-5HsDMYn-r7tzypG-OKMJ5A7e5xBE=\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Fixing compilation issues**\\n\\nI need to resolve a compilation issue. It seems Scala 2.13 doesn't support `scala.annotation.static`, and I’m wondering if I need a static method in an object. Scala objects compile as instance methods in a module, possibly creating a static forwarder. If it’s a top-level object, the `Reflection` package might offer a static forwarder unless it’s nested. Also, Scala 2.11+ generates static forwarders for top-level modules, while Java reflection has both static and instance methods visible. I'll verify if companion classes influence this.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Resolving companion issues**\\n\\nI’m considering if static forwarders are added to a companion class when it exists, without using `@static`. Is there a conflict, though? The `sun.reflect` package is in the `jdk.unsupported` module, and while the Scala compiler might allow its use, would a Java file conflict? If I remove imports and annotations, could I use `Class.forName(\\\"sun.reflect.Reflection\\\")` in JDK 21? I must think about package sealing and whether the class loader can define classes in `sun.reflect`. I'll just remove `@static` but I need to confirm the method is static.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Inspecting static forwarders**\\n\\nI’m considering whether I should only use a Scala object. I need to check if it creates static forwarders when there's a companion class, as Scala 2.13 might handle that. The user mentioned an error, but I'm not sure if I should compile or run tests myself; it might be better to refrain from that. I recall that `@static` might have been introduced in Scala 2.12, not in 2.13. I need to clarify this to proceed correctly.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_BeSw7btuvur1F99qaEoONIsj|fc_01a34b971ae9a67b0169fb1dea6898819c8a8106d4282da07b", "name": "edit", "